<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="131" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,403,2014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,330,403,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">New diagnosis.</emphasis>
Medium size (
<quantity box="[502,621,403,430]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" unit="mm" value="21.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="20.0">20-23 mm</quantity>
) and moderately robust. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[906,1042,403,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Coloration.</emphasis>
The only species included for this genus are brown with light yellow spots on the body (
<figureCitation box="[780,855,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
A-C), more noticeable on the legs, and black face (common in several genera of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[585,702,475,502]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleminiini">pleminiini</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[724,809,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[830,901,475,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Head.</emphasis>
In front view ovoid, space between the antennal basins, as wide as half of the antennal scapus; fastigium slightly high and narrow; round and small eyes (
<figureCitation box="[1334,1421,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
), in dorsal view, a little bit shorter than the margins of the antennal sockets. Ocelli reduced and diffused; scapus and pedicelus unarmed; maxillary palps moderately elongated (
<figureCitation box="[833,910,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
A-B). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[989,1110,583,609]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Pronotum</emphasis>
slightly granulated, anterior margin projected onto the neck, in the prozone on the side edge only indicated with a longitudinal fold, the metazone not widened (
<figureCitation box="[307,373,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[399,482,655,681]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Wings.</emphasis>
Tegmina is almost longer than the pronotum, broadly lanceolate, densely reticulate, with slightly prominent veins and an apex narrowly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[839,971,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Figs. 1A, C</figureCitation>
); hind wings are reduced as small hyaline lobes. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[225,281,727,753]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Legs</emphasis>
slender, fore coxa armed with a conspicuous dorsal spine; all coxae are ventrally unarmed; fore femur not very strong compressed; mid tibia moderately grooved, dorsally unarmed, and all inner genicular lobes armed with a tiny blunt spine. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[411,528,799,825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Abdomen</emphasis>
cylindrical, without modifications on the segments, epiproctus small and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[160,250,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
). Reduced and conical cerci; ovipositor as long as two-thirds of the length of the hind femur, moderately curved and with a sinuous dorsal edge, pointed apex (
<figureCitation box="[748,833,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate rectangular, wider than long, with a rather prolonged posterior border and with a medial notch (
<figureCitation box="[815,899,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
). Male unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="131" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,403,2014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,355,943,969]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,943,969]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895)" baseAuthorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[362,987,943,970]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrifrons">
<emphasis box="[362,622,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelidius atrifrons</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." box="[637,979,943,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" pagination="1 - 282" refId="ref3862" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1895) Monographie der Pseudophylliden. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch- Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 45, 1 - 282." type="journal article" year="1895">Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
by original designation. Herein, the genus is regarded as monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="131" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,403,2014]" box="[199,568,1015,1041]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1015,1041]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Distribution.</emphasis>
Colombian Andes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,403,2014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,1051,1077]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Comparison.</emphasis>
This genus is close to others of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[816,934,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleminiini">pleminiini</taxonomicName>
, with a black face, medium-size and slender. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1954" box="[151,307,1087,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,307,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has distinguished from the other genera in that the spines on the legs are medium to small in size, in contrast to the related genera of the tribe, which have moderately to well-developed lamellar spines. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1954" box="[1281,1437,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1281,1437,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the morphologically similar genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Redtenbacher" authorityYear="1895" box="[690,816,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[690,816,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to its smaller size (
<quantity box="[1087,1213,1159,1186]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" unit="mm" value="21.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="20.0">20-23 mm</quantity>
.); absence of spines on the fore and mid tibiae’s dorsal margin; brown body coloration, and densely reticulate venation. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Redtenbacher" authorityYear="1895" box="[151,277,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,277,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups larger species (
<quantity box="[543,668,1231,1258]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" unit="mm" value="30.0" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="25.0">25-35 mm</quantity>
.), with spines on the dorsal margin, venation with notorious spaces between the transverse and longitudinal veins, forming medium-sized cells. Additionally, the 
<taxonomicName box="[1220,1436,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1220,1346,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
have a coloration from dark brown, passing through grayish green, the pronotum is granular, and sometimes forming conspicuous tubercles, which resemble spines, that surround the pronotal disc as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilatatus">
<emphasis box="[1133,1364,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelus dilatatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." pageId="2" pageNumber="131" pagination="1 - 282" refId="ref3862" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1895) Monographie der Pseudophylliden. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch- Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 45, 1 - 282." type="journal article" year="1895">Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="133" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,403,2014]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1411,1437]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1954" box="[343,499,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[343,499,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered monotypic in this contribution. The female 
<typeStatus box="[1152,1200,1412,1438]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" baseAuthorityYear="1895" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">D. atrifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has part of the rectum extracted outwards, protruding between the cerci, and it can be confused with the epiproct at first sight (
<figureCitation box="[397,470,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1419,192,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,179,1912]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dasyscelidius atrifrons (Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895) Female holotype. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C. Habitus in dorsal view. D-F. Terminalia: D. Dorsal. E. Lateral and F. Ventral views respectively. “© by Natural History Museum Vienna, NOaS Image Collection / H. Bruckner; published with permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037015/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
D-E). The exact locality of the species is unknown since, in its description, it was only mentioned that it was collected from 
<collectingCountry box="[569,679,1519,1545]" name="Colombia" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." box="[694,1038,1519,1546]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" pagination="1 - 282" refId="ref3862" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1895) Monographie der Pseudophylliden. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch- Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 45, 1 - 282." type="journal article" year="1895">Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895</bibRefCitation>
). Recently, iNaturalist observations (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70049414, https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/67625294) and an examined female from 
<collectingRegion box="[412,493,1591,1617]" country="Colombia" name="Bogota" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Bogotá</collectingRegion>
(deposited in CAUD, and agree with 
<typeStatus box="[918,966,1592,1618]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">type</typeStatus>
description and measurements), being inhabitants of the Eastern Hills, where they cohabit with an undescribed genus and species, superficially very similar, although belonging to the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[500,648,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platyphyllini">Platyphyllini</taxonomicName>
. This is one of the reasons to clarify the status and tribal location of the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,399,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[151,307,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelidius</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, thus being the object of differentiation between the short-winged Andean taxa of the tribes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[151,268,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleminiini">Pleminiini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[324,472,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platyphyllini">Platyphyllini</taxonomicName>
, which could be confused (Medellin 
<emphasis box="[890,940,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">et al</emphasis>
. in prep.). The other species included in the genus by 
<bibRefCitation author="Beier, M." box="[259,394,1771,1798]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" refId="ref3748" refString="Beier, M. (1954) Revision der Pseudophyllinen. Instituto EspanTol de Entomologiia, Madrid, 479 pp." type="book" year="1954">Beier (1954</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Beier, M." box="[405,462,1771,1798]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" pagination="468" refId="ref3769" refString="Beier, M. (1962) Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Pseudophyllinae I). In: Mertens, R., Hennig, W. &amp; Wermuth, H. (Eds.), Das Tierreich. Vol. 73. Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co., Berlin, pp. 468." type="book chapter" year="1962">1962</bibRefCitation>
) have the following taxonomic changes:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,403,2014]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="133" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">
We propose 
<taxonomicName authority="(Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895)" baseAuthorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[338,959,1807,1834]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minimus">
<emphasis box="[338,596,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Dasyscelidius minimus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." box="[610,951,1807,1834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" pagination="1 - 282" refId="ref3862" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1895) Monographie der Pseudophylliden. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch- Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 45, 1 - 282." type="journal article" year="1895">Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
as 
<emphasis box="[996,1162,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">nomen dubium</emphasis>
. Unfortunately, the only known specimen of the species is lost. It was deposited in the Lübeck Museum (
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1157,1843,1869]" name="Germany" pageId="2" pageNumber="131">Germany</collectingCountry>
), but its original description in Latin and its short diagnosis provided later by 
<bibRefCitation author="Beier, M." box="[737,877,1879,1906]" pageId="2" pageNumber="131" refId="ref3748" refString="Beier, M. (1954) Revision der Pseudophyllinen. Instituto EspanTol de Entomologiia, Madrid, 479 pp." type="book" year="1954">Beier (1954)</bibRefCitation>
in German is not informative, as the sample below translated into English: “small and delicate, yellowish-brown with darker spots, frons darkened, pronotum short, flat, densely and uniformly granulated, dorsally yellowish and laterally chestnut-brown; tegmina strongly reduced, in male not extending beyond first abdominal segment, touching in the midline, densely reticulated; sternum black; legs yellowish with dark mottling; all genicular lobes pointed; male cerci fairly long, styli very short” (
<bibRefCitation author="Cigliano, M. M. &amp; Braun, H. &amp; Eades, D. C. &amp; Otte, D." pageId="4" pageNumber="133" refId="ref4116" refString="Cigliano, M. M., Braun, H., Eades, D. C. &amp; Otte, D. (2022) Orthoptera Species File. Version 5.0 / 5.0. Available from: http: // Orthoptera. SpeciesFile. org (accessed 12 January 2021)" type="url" year="2022">
Cigliano 
<emphasis box="[198,247,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">et al</emphasis>
., 2022
</bibRefCitation>
). Several 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[437,554,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleminiini">Pleminiini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[607,752,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platyphyllini">Platyphyllini</taxonomicName>
brachypteran taxa have been described in recent years. However, genera and species of other tribes of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1838" box="[614,799,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pseudophyllinae">Pseudophyllinae</taxonomicName>
are also brachypterous (
<bibRefCitation author="Braun, H." box="[1068,1211,223,249]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" refId="ref3824" refString="Braun, H. (2002) Die Laubheuschrecken (Orthoptera, Tettigoniidae) eines Bergregenwaldes in Sud-Ecuador - faunistische, bioakustische und okologische Untersuchungen. PhD Thesis, University of Erlangen-Nurnberg, Erlangen, 142 pp." type="book" year="2002">Braun, 2002</bibRefCitation>
; Cadena-Castañeda, 2011; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Braun, H." box="[220,603,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="34 - 38" refId="ref3939" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Braun, H. (2011) A new brachypterous genus of Platyphyllini (Orthoptera, Tettigoniidae, Pseudophyllinae) from Colombia. Zootaxa, 2763 (1), 34 - 38. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2763.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Braun, 2011</bibRefCitation>
; Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Monzón, 2014; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Parra, N. O. &amp; Tavares, G. &amp; Trujillo, D. M. &amp; Quintana, R. F." box="[1034,1377,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="546 - 562" refId="ref4033" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J., Parra, N. O., Tavares, G., Trujillo, D. M. &amp; Quintana, R. F. (2021) Studies on Neotropical Pseudophyllinae: The status of the genus Brachyauchenus Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1895 and its species (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae). Zootaxa, 5027 (4), 546 - 562. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5027.4.4" type="journal article" year="2021">
Cadena-Castañeda 
<emphasis box="[1248,1297,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">et al</emphasis>
., 2021
</bibRefCitation>
), and the characters specified by Beier are not enough to make a suitable identification. In addition, they coincide with several of the known Andean brachypterous species and many others that are still unknown to science.
</paragraph>
